1A27; color:white;\" |Place||{{Tooltip|DNS|Did not start}}||{{Tooltip|DNF|Did not finish}}||{{Tooltip|DSQ|Disqualified}}\n|-\n! style=\"background:#0E1A27; color:white;\" |Points||-4|| colspan=\"2\" |-2\n|}\n\n===Skin races===\nA skin race is a series of back-to-back-to-back 50 meters (SCM) freestyle races, operating on a knockout basis: First round four swimmers are eliminated (out of 8), second round two swimmers are knocked out,  3rd and last round thus consists of only two swimmers racing each other in a head-to-head final race. Skin races\u2019 rounds are held every 3 minutes. The athletes can warm down in the pool or can get a short massage from their team's physiotherapist behind the blocks between each round until the 3 minutes are done. The athletes knocked out of the race must return to their team's area.<br>\nThe lanes, that the qualified athletes will use in the following round, are to be determined according to their team's lane assignment for the day.<ref name=format /> ISL skin races score as follows:\n\n{|class=\"wikitable\" text-align=\"center\"\n!style=\"background:#FFFFFF; border-top:solid 1px #FFFFFF; border-left:solid 1px #FFFFFF;\"\"| !!style='background:#0E1A27; color:white;'|Place||{{Tooltip|DNS|Did not start}}||{{Tooltip|DNF|Did not finish}}||{{Tooltip|DSQ|Disqualified}}||8th||7th||6th||5th||4th||3rd||2nd||1st\n|-\n!style='background:#0E1A27; color:white;'|Round 1!!style='background:#0E1A27; color:white;'|Points||-4||colspan=\"2\"|-2||1||2||3||4||colspan=\"2\" style=\"background:#FFFFFF;  border-right:solid 1px #FFFFFF;\"\"| ||colspan=\"2\" style=\"background:#FFFFFF; border-bottom:solid 1px #FFFFFF; border-left:solid 1px #FFFFFF; border-right:solid 1px #FFFFFF;\"\"| \n|-\n!style='background:#0E1A27; color:white;'|Round 2!!style='background:#0E1A27; color:white;'|Points||-8||colspan=\"2\"|-4||colspan=\"4\" style=\"background:#FFFFFF;  border-bottom:solid 1px #FFFFFF;\"\"|  ||10||12||colspan=\"2\" style=\"background:#FFFFFF; border-top:solid 1px #FFFFFF; border-right:solid 1px #FFFFFF;\"\"|  \n|-\n!style='background:#0E1A27; color:white;'|Round 3!!style=\"background:#0E1A27; color:white;\"|Points||-12||colspan=\"2\"|-6||colspan=\"6\" style=\"background:#FFFFFF; border-bottom:solid 1px #FFFFFF;\"\"| ||21||27\n|}\n\n===MVP===\nAn MVP is selected after each match and at the end of the season. The criteria for such selections are the number of points towards the team score, that the swimmer has accumulated during the match and the season respectively.<ref name=format />\nEach time, only one MVP can be elected and can be both a woman or a man. The MVP prize at the end of each match rewards a 5,000$ bonus.\n\n=== 2020 Technical Novelties ===\n\n==Prizes==\nA points system \u2013 awarding from 6 down to 1 point for the top four athletes (and teams) in each event\u2013 has been created to establish how the prize money should be divided (relays score double points, skin races score triple points).<ref name=format /><ref>Each swimmer receives 25% of team\u2019s relay points.</ref>\nBased on how many points an athlete scored and on how many matches he attended, the prize money can further increase if his team has qualified for the Final Match.\n\n{|class=\"wikitable\" style=\"color:0E1A27;\"\n!style='background:#0E1A27; color:white;'|Prize money!!style='background:#0E1A27; color:white;'|Details\n|-\n|style=\"text-align:center;\"|$ 10000||per swimmers in winner Club at Final Match\n|-\n|style=\"text-align:center;\"|$ 5000||per swimmers in second-placed Club at Final Match\n|-\n|style=\"text-align:center;\"|$ 3000||per swimmers in third-placed Club at Final Match\n|-\n|rowspan=\"4\" style=\"text-align:center;\"|$ 1000||per swimmers in fourth-placed Club at Final Match\n|-\n|per point in Final Match (per swimmer)\n|-\n|per match attended (per swimmer)\n|-\n|per match attended at Final Match (per swimmer)\n|-\n|style=\"text-align:center;\"|$ 300||per point in regular season matches\n|}\n\nThe prize money leader of the inaugural season was Sarah Sjostrom with a total of $139,700.<ref name=\"swimswam.com\">https://swimswam.com/sarah-sjostrom-tops-isl-season-prize-money-list-with-139-7k-earnings/</ref><ref name=\"swimswam.com\"/>\n\n== Budget ==\nThe 2019 season budget was US$20m, with over US$6m of this being appearance and prize money for the athletes.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.insidethegames.biz/articles/1076461/international-swimming-league-to-have-first-year-budget-of-20-million|title=Grigorishin said that between $6 million|last=|first=|date=7 March 2019|website=www.insidethegames.biz|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-02-06}}</ref>\n\n==Results by season==\n{|class = \"wikitable\"\n!style='background:#0E1A27; color:white;'|Season\n!style='background:#0E1A27; color:white;'|{{Tooltip|Rds|Rounds}}\n!style='background:#0E1A27; color:white;'|Champion\n!style='background:#0E1A27; color:white;'|Second\n!style='background:#0E1A27; color:white;'|Third\n!style='background:#0E1A27; color:white;'|Fourth\n|-\n|align=center|[[2019 International Swimming League|2019]]\n|align=center|7\n| align=center|{{flagicon|FRA}} Energy Standard\n| align=center|{{flagicon|GBR}} London Roar\n| align=center|{{flagicon|USA}} Cali Condors\n| align=center|{{flagicon|USA}} LA Current\n|}\n\n== History ==\n\n===FINA-ISL dispute===\nAt the start of the [[2018 in aquatic sports|2018 season]], the only major annual swimming tournament sanctioned by [[FINA]] was [[FINA Swimming World Cup]]. In order to ensure swimming greater visibility through a new team-based format, a new organization - founded in 2017 and named '''International Swimming League''' - was presented in [[Anaheim, California|Anaheim]] on September 2018, based on the idea of [[Ukrainia]]n billionaire [[Konstantin Grigorishin]]:<ref name=\"19/making-a-splash\">[https://www.theguardian.com/sport/2019/jun/19/making-a-splash-new-big-money-competition-shakes-up-swimming Making a splash: new big-money competition shakes up swimming], [[The Guardian]] (18 June 2019)</ref> the inaugural event of the new league would have been the annual meeting ''Energy for Swim'' (held for the first time in 2017 and scheduled for 20\u201321 December in [[Turin]],Italy in that season).<ref>{{cite news|url=https://swimswam.com/international-swimming-league-2018-event-to-launch-with-2-1-million-in-prize-and-appearance-money-2/|title=International Swimming League Presents At The 2018 ASCA World Clinic|date=8 September 2018|work=SwimSwam|access-date=10 October 2019}}</ref> In June, FINA sent a letter to all 209 federations, urging them not to cooperate with ISL.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.insidethegames.biz/media/file/109700/fina_memorandum_to_all_fina_members_-_05.06.2018-2.pdf|title=Memorandum to all FINA members|date=5 June 2018|work=Inside the games|format=pdf|access-date=10 October 2019}}</ref>\n\nAfter clarifying the interpretation of a rule included in section 4.5 of FINA general rules,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://cdn.swimswam.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/11/logo_fina_general_rules_as_approved_by_the_ec_on_22.07.2017_final_4_15102018.pdf|title=FINA General Rules|publisher=FINA|format=pdf|access-date=10 October 2019}}</ref> FINA stated that the ''Energy for swim'' meet was now classified as an international event for that season, given that \"a competition which is conceptually designed to have a majority of foreign participants is not a national competition\u201d, and thus it needed to be approved within the ordinary six-month window.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://swimswam.com/fina-rule-interpretation-could-outlaw-energy-for-swim-meet/|title=FINA Rule Interpretation Could Outlaw Energy For Swim Meet|date=2 November 2018|work=SwimSwam|access-date=10 October 2019}}</ref>\n\nSince the approval window was already expired, the athletes participating in that meet would have been disqualified from one to two years by FINA and any world records set during the event would not have been recognized.\n\nThe negotiations between the parties officially broke down on 15 November 2018, eventually leading to ''Energy for Swim'' meet cancellation.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.insidethegames.biz/articles/1072303/rival-swimming-competition-cancelled-after-fina-threaten-action-against-swimmers|title=Rival swimming competition cancelled after FINA threaten action against swimmers|date=16 November 2018|work=Inside the games|access-date=10 October 2019}}</ref>\n\n===Debut===\nDespite negotiations failure between FINA, ISL and Energy for Standard Group - that would have organized ''Energy for Standard'' meet along with [[Italian Swimming Federation|FIN]] - several athletes sustained the new idea of a team-based swimming competition (among which [[Katinka Hosszu]] and [[Adam Peaty]]). FINA announced on December 2018 the creation of a brand new league, called [[FINA Champions Swim Series]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.fina.org/news/pr-107-fina-approves-new-world-class-swimming-event|title=PR 107 - FINA approves new world-class swimming event|date=13 December 2018|work=FINA|access-date=10 October 2019}}</ref>\nThe first ISL team to be officially announced was German side ''ONEFlow Aquatics'' (that wouldn't have taken part to the inaugural season, eventually) on January 2019, after which ISL announced also the remaining three European teams and the four American teams in the following months.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://swimswam.com/oneflow-aquatic-announced-as-newest-team-in-isl/|title=ONEFlow Aquatic Announced as Newest Team in ISL|date=10 January 2019|work=SwimSwam|access-date=10 October 2019}}</ref><br>\nMeanwhile, ISL also presented a newly formed representation company - '''ISL USA''' - which would have staged the semifinals and Final Match, at [[Mandalay Bay]] in [[Las Vegas]], and assisted the new US clubs in their operations (including scouting talent, signing athletes and running their own swimming meets).<ref>{{cite news|url=https://isl.global/the-isl-usa-is-now-officially-up-and-running/|title=The ISL USA is Now Officially Up And Running|date=24 January 2019|work=ISL|access-date=10 October 2019}}</ref> A crucial step towards the creation of ISL was made when FINA announced that athletes taking part to Non-FINA sanctioned events wouldn't have been banned and that similar competitions would be allowed, also confirming that all the world records set in the first two stages wouldn't have been considered (because of clashing with [[2019 FINA Swimming World Cup|World Cup]] events).<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.swimmingworldmagazine.com/news/fina-provides-clarification-on-athlete-participation-in-international-competitions/|title=FINA Provides Clarification on Athlete Participation in International Competitions|date=15 January 2019|work=Swimming World Magazine|access-date=10 October 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.swimmingworldmagazine.com/news/fina-would-approve-league-world-records-to-avoid-escalation-of-swimmers-revolution/|title=FINA \u2018Would Approve League World Records To Avoid Escalation Of Swimmers\u2019 Revolution\u2019|date=8 October 2019|work=Swimming World Magazine|access-date=21 October 2019}}</ref><br>\nIn June 2019, ISL released the schedule of the league second\u03a9 season, that officially started on the first week of the following October.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://isl.global/international-swimming-league-announces-cities-and-venues%e2%80%a8-world-class-athletes-to-compete-in-seven-cities-worldwide/|title=INTERNATIONAL SWIMMING LEAGUE ANNOUNCES CITIES AND VENUES|date=21 June 2019|work=ISL|accessdate=10 October 2019}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n[[Category:International Swimming League| ]]\n[[Category:Swimming competitions]]\n[[Category:Recurring sporting events established in 2019]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Professional swimming league}}\n{{Infobox sports league\n| upcoming_season = <!--comment out, do not delete--> \n| last_season     = <!--comment out, do not delete--> \n| current_season  = <!--comment out, do not delete--> 2019 International Swimming League\n| logo            = \n| logo_size       =\n| caption         =\n| sport           = [[Swimming (sport)|Swimming]]\n| founded         = 2019\n| president       = [[Konstantin Grigorishin]]\n| ceo             = Ali Khan\n| teams           = 10\n| countries       = Worldwide\n| champion        = \n| most_champs     = \n| website         = https://isl.global/\n}}\n\nThe '''International Swimming League''' ('''ISL''') is an annual professional [[Swimming (sport)|swimming]] league, established in 2019. It features a team-based\ncompetition format with fast-paced race sessions. In 2019, the regular season started in October and the Final Match was held in December.\n\nAthletes previously disqualified for breaking anti-doping rules are banned from ISL.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://isl.global/competition-format/|title=Competition format|work=ISL|access-date=10 October 2019}}</ref>\n\n== Format ==\n\n=== ISL Season ===\nThe season is split into a regular championship and a final. In the regular championship clubs earn points from participating in matches according to the following principle: 4 points for 1st place in the match, 3 for 2nd, 2 for 3rd and 1 for 4th. After all of the championship matches, 4 clubs with the highest number of points advance to the final, where the winner of the league (the ISL Champions) are determined. Each club can have a maximum roster of 32 athletes. At each match 28 of these are permitted to compete - 12 men and 12 women can swim individual races, while 2 men and 2 women can be used as \"relay only\" athletes.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://isl.global/isl-2019-technical-information/|title=ISL 2019 technical information \u2013 International Swimming League|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-10}}</ref>\n\n=== ISL Matches ===\nFour clubs take part in a match. During the first season, an ISL match consisted of 37 races: 30 individual, 5 team relays and 2 skin races. Each race consists of 2 representatives from each of the clubs. Points are distributed after the race in the following manner: 9 points for 1st, 7 for 2nd, ... 1 for 8th. Points are not awarded to athletes (teams) that fail to finish a race. In addition, points are doubled in relays and are awarded after each of the 3 skin race heats.\n\nThe points of the clubs\u2019 representatives are then added together and go towards the total points result of their respective clubs.\n\nA victory in a race does not guarantee maximum club points. As an example, club representatives that finish 1st and 7th in a race will earn less points for their respective clubs than those who finish 2nd and 4th: they will score 11 and 12 total points, respectively.\n\nA match is won by the club that has scored the most points in all of the 37 races. Similarly, the rest of the clubs are distributed through 2nd to 4th place, respective of the points they score during the entire match. Theoretically, a match could be won by a team that has not won a single race.\n\nIn case 2 or more clubs end up with the same amount of points after the match, an extra mixed medley 4x50m relay shall take place, the outcome of which will mirror the final results of the match.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://isl.global/isl-2019-technical-information/|title=ISL 2019 technical information \u2013 International Swimming League|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-08}}</ref>\n<br />\n==Teams==\nThe [[2019 International Swimming League|inaugural league]] debuted with eight teams across two conferences, four from the United States, and four from Europe. Each team appeared in a pair of inter-conference matches involving two teams from each conference, one in America and one in Europe, and a \"derby\" match involving all four teams from its own conference. The top two teams in each conference met in a Grand final in [[Las Vegas]].\n\nAt the 2019 Grand Final, the ISL announced a further two franchises, as yet unnamed, would be joining an expanded ISL for 2020; one from Toronto and one from Tokyo. Toronto will be joining the Americas Conference, while Tokyo will join a renamed European-Asian Conference. In addition, a much larger match programme, with a minimum of ten matches per team (up from 3 in 2019) was announced.<ref>[https://www.cbc.ca/sports/olympics/summer/aquatics/international-swimming-league-final-day-two-recap-1.5406086 ISL League final recap, Toronto and Tokyo added for 2020]</ref>\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! style=\"background:white\"|Team\n! style=\"background:white\"|City\n! style=\"background:white\"|Joined\n! style=\"background:white\"|General Manager\n! style=\"background:white\"|Head Coach\n|-\n! style=\"background:#1D428A;\" colspan=\"5\"|<span style=\"color:#FFFFFF;\">Americas Conference</span>\n|-\n| '''D.C. Trident'''\n| {{flagicon|USA}} [[Washington, D.C.]]\n| 2019\n| [[Kaitlin Sandeno]]\n| Cyndi Gallagher\n|-\n|''' L.A. Current'''\n| {{flagicon|USA}} [[Los Angeles]] \n| 2019\n| [[Lenny Krayzelburg]]\n| [[David Marsh (swimming coach)|David Marsh]]\n|-\n|''' New York Breakers'''\n| {{flagicon|USA}} [[New York City]]\n| 2019\n| Tina Andrew\n| Peter Andrew\n|-\n| '''Cali Condors'''\n| {{flagicon|USA}} [[San Francisco]]\n| 2019\n| [[Jason Lezak]]\n| [[Gregg Troy]]\n|-\n| '''Toronto Titans'''\n| {{flagicon|CAN}} [[Toronto]]\n| 2020\n| Robert Kent\n| \n|-\n! style=\"background:#C8102E;\" colspan=\"5\"|<span style=\"color:#FFFFFF;\">European-Asian Conference</span>\n|-\n| '''Energy Standard'''\n| {{flagicon|FRA}} [[Paris]]\n| 2019\n| Jean-Francois Salessy \n| [[James Gibson (swimmer)|James Gibson]]\n|-\n| '''London Roar'''\n| {{flagicon|GBR}} [[London]]\n| 2019\n| [[Rob Woodhouse]]\n| [[Mel Marshall]]\n|-\n| '''Team Iron'''\n| {{flagicon|HUN}} [[Budapest]]\n| 2019\n| [[Dorina Szekeres]]\n| \n|-\n| '''Aqua Centurions'''\n| {{flagicon|ITA}} [[Rome]]\n| 2019\n| Alessandra Guerra\n| [[Matteo Giunta]]\n|-\n| ''ISL Tokyo''\n| {{flagicon|JPN}}  [[Tokyo]]\n| 2020\n|[[Kosuke Kitajima]]\n| \n|}\n\n==Technical Rules==\nAll the matches are comprised of four clubs and take place on two days, with two 2-hour long sessions including two short breaks in each. In each event, all the clubs competing must line up two athletes (and also two teams in the relays), with a consistent lane assignment throughout the day, which is randomly assigned at the start of each match.<ref name=format></ref> Team line-ups are submitted prior to each competition session. These line-ups can be changed and adjusted during the scheduled breaks within the competition. This has to be done 2-minutes after the conclusion of the last event in the previous session.\nIn 2019 there was total of 37 races, and in 2020 a total of 39 races, among individual events, relay and skin races, are held during one match (the 4x50 medley mixed relay will only be held if two teams tie in points at the end of all the previous races).<ref name=format>{{cite web|url=https://isl.global/isl-2019-technical-information/|title=ISL 2019 technical information|work=ISL|access-date=10 October 2019}}</ref><br>\nPoints are awarded to the teams at the end of each match as follows:\n\n{|class=\"wikitable\"\n!style='background:#0E1A27; color:white;'|Place||1st||2nd||3rd||4th\n|-\n!style='background:#0E1A27; color:white;'|Points||4||3||2||1\n|}\n\nIn 2019, the two American and European teams with most points in standings at the end of the regular season advance to the Final Match (if two teams are tied, cumulative points of these clubs will be taken into account and if still tied there will be a swim-off, which will be 4x50 medley mixed).<br>\nThe scoring for each individual event is as follows (relays races will score double the points):<ref name=format></ref>\n\n{|class=\"wikitable\"\n!style='background:#0E1A27; color:white;'|Place||1st||2nd||3rd||4th||5th||6th||7th||8th||{{Tooltip|DNF|Did not finish}}||{{Tooltip|DSQ|Disqualified}}||{{Tooltip|DNS|Did not start}}\n|-\n!style='background:#0E1A27; color:white;'|Points||9||7||6||5||4||3||2||1||colspan=\"2\"|-2||-4\n|}\n\n===Relay races===\nA particular points scoring system has been introduced for relay races, which score double points than individual events. In order to force athletes to put their best forward every time they step on the blocks and to avoid a lack of engagement, minimum time standards have been established.   \n\n{|\n|- valign=top\n|\n{|class=\"wikitable\"\n!style='background:#0E1A27; color:white;'|Place||1st||2nd||3rd||4th||5th||6th||7th||8th\n|-\n!style='background:#0E1A27; color:white;'|Points||18||14||12||10||8||6||4||2\n|}\n|}\n\n=== Penalties ===\nIf a relay or swimmer is slower than the times indicated in the table below, it gets a penalty of points A relay slower than the time standard gets 2 points deducted whereas an athlete slower than the respective time indicated gets instead 1 point of penalty.\n\nOn the table all of the minimum time standards (SCM) for the events are compared to the world records.\n{|\n|\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"background:#eaecf0; text-align:center;\"\n! style=\"background:#FFFFFF; border-top:solid 1px #FFFFFF; border-left:solid 1px #FFFFFF;\" \" |  !! style=\"background:#0E1A27; color:white;\" |Distance!! style=\"background:#0E1A27; color:white;\" |Men!! style=\"background:#0E1A27; color:white;\" |World Record!! rowspan=\"23\" style=\"background:#0E1A27; font-size:0.2em; line-height:0.5px;;\" |&nbsp;!! style=\"background:#0E1A27; color:white;\" |Women!! style=\"background:#0E1A27; color:white;\" |World Record\n|-\n| rowspan=\"4\" |[[Freestyle (swimming)|Freestyle]]||50||22.50||20.26||25.50||22.93\n|-\n|100||49.50||44.94||55.00||50.25\n|-\n|200||1:49.50||1:39.37||1:58.50||1:50.43\n|-\n|400||3:50.50||3:32.25||4:10.00||3:53.92\n|-\n| colspan=\"4\" style=\"background:#0E1A27; font-size:0.2em; line-height:0.5px;;\" |&nbsp;|| colspan=\"2\" style=\"background:#0E1A27; font-size:0.2em; line-height:0.5px;;\" |&nbsp;\n|-\n| rowspan=\"3\" |[[Backstroke]]||50||25.00||22.22||28.50||