{"title_page": "Qonqurtai", "text_new": "{{copy edit|date=April 2020}}\n\n{{Infobox royalty|name=Qonqurtai|spouse-type=|regent=|queen=|religion=|mother=Ajuja|father=[[Hulagu Khan]]|house-type=Dynasty|house=[[Borjigin]]|issue=|death_place=[[Karabakh]], [[Ilkhanate]]|image=|death_date=18 January 1284|birth_place=[[Mongolia]]|birth_date=|successor=|predecessor=|reign=1277 - 1282 <br> 12 July 1282 - 18 January 1284|succession=Viceroy of [[Anatolia]]|caption=|reg-type=}}'''Qonqurtai''' ({{Lang-fa|\u0642\u0648\u0646\u0642\u0648\u0631\u062a\u0627\u0649}}) was a Mongal prince and viceroy of [[Anatolia]] for the [[Ilkhanate]] [[khanate]].\n\n== Life ==\nQonqurtai was born to [[Hulagu Khan]] and Ajuja Aguchi, his [[Khitan people|Khitan]] concubine wife. Qonqurtai was Hulagu's ninth son and was the senior commander during the reign of his brother [[Abaqa Khan|Abaqa]]. He was twice appointed as viceroy of Anatolia, first during the reign of Abaqa and then under [[Tekuder]]. His winter quarters were in [[:tr: Kazova|Kazova]] plains near [[Tokat]], while his vice royalty itself has centered around [[Kayseri]].\n\n== Rule in Anatolia ==\nHe was appointed as commander of Ilkhanid army in Anatolia with [[Shams al-Din Juvayni]] as his vizier after the [[Battle of Elbistan]] in 1277 to support the [[Sultanate of Rum]] against revolting Turcomans.<ref>{{Cite book|last=Lane, George, 1952-|first=|url=https://www.worldcat.org/oclc/890796255|title=Early Mongol rule in thirteenth-century Iran : a Persian renaissance|publisher=|year=|isbn=978-1-134-43103-8|location=London|pages=201|oclc=890796255}}</ref>He pursed [[Jimri]], a claimant to Seljuk throne and attacked his patrons - the [[Karamanids]]. As a consequence, [[Mehmet I of Karaman]] was captured and executed together with his sons Mahmud and Karaman in October 1277.<ref>{{Cite book|last=|first=|url=https://www.worldcat.org/oclc/219570995|title=The Cambridge history of Turkey|publisher=|others=Fleet, Kate., Faroqhi, Suraiya, 1941-, Kasaba, Re\u015fat, 1954-|year=|isbn=978-0-521-62093-2|location=New York|pages=70|oclc=219570995}}</ref> He further authorised [[S\u00e2hib Ata]] to act on his behalf. He aided [[Kaykhusraw III]]'s efforts to subdue Karamanids and [[Eshrefids]] in 1282. However, he had to cease his activities upon hearing death of Abaqa.\n\nUpon the death of [[Abaqa Khan|Abaqa]], he supported [[Tekuder]]'s succession in [[Maragheh|Maragha]], who in return gave him the hand of Toqiyatai Khatun, a [[Keraites|Keraite]] concubine of Hulagu and niece of [[Doquz Khatun|Dokuz Khatun]] on 12 July 1282. He was also re-appointed as viceroy of Anatolia the same day.<ref>{{Cite book|last=Nicola|first=Bruno De|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=MjZYDwAAQBAJ|title=Women in Mongol Iran: The Khatuns, 1206-1335|date=2017-03-08|publisher=Edinburgh University Press|isbn=978-1-4744-1549-1|language=en}}</ref>However, later in Tekuder's reign, he shifted his alliance to [[Arghun]], which made the former suspicious. Qonqurtai was summoned to Karabakh, accused of conspiracy and was arrested by Teg\u00fcder's son-in-law, Alinaq - the viceroy of [[Georgia (country)|Georgia]] on 17 January 1284 and was executed next day by breaking his neck.<ref>{{Cite book|last=Nicola|first=Bruno De|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=RgpRDAAAQBAJ|title=The Mongols' Middle East: Continuity and Transformation in Ilkhanid Iran|last2=Melville|first2=Charles|date=2016-06-09|publisher=BRILL|year=|isbn=978-90-04-31472-6|location=|pages=113|language=en}}</ref> Later Arghun had put Tekuder on trial for Qonqurtai's death, who suffered the same penalty as him.\n\n== Personality ==\nHe was described as a wise ruler in ''[[Zafarnamah (Mustawfi)|Zafarnamah]]'' by [[Hamdallah Mustawfi|Hamdullah Mustawfi]]<ref name=\":0\">L. J. Ward, \u201cThe \u1e92afar-n\u0101mah of \u1e24amd All\u0101h Mustaufi and the Il-Kh\u0101n dynasty of Iran,\u201d Ph.D. diss, p.204, University of Manchester, 1983.</ref>, while [[Al-Mansur Qalawun|Qalawun]] considered him as a dishonorable and cruel man.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Allouche|first=Adel|date=1990|title=Teg\u00fcder's Ultimatum to Qalawun|url=https://www.cambridge.org/core/product/identifier/S0020743800034358/type/journal_article|journal=International Journal of Middle East Studies|language=en|volume=22|issue=4|pages=437\u2013446|doi=10.1017/S0020743800034358|issn=0020-7438|via=}}</ref>\n\n== Family ==\nHe was married to Toqiyatai Khatun (d. 1292), a [[Keraites|Keraite]] concubine of Hulagu and niece of [[Doquz Khatun|Dokuz Khatun]] on 12 July 1282, and only two of his children reached adulthood.<ref name=\":0\" />:\n\n# Esen Timur Kharbanda (executed by [[Ghazan]] in 1296<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|url=https://deepblue.lib.umich.edu/handle/2027.42/133445|title=Mediating Sacred Kingship: Conversion and Sovereignty in Mongol Iran|website=deepblue.lib.umich.edu|access-date=2020-04-06}}</ref>)\n## Pulad\n# Ildar (executed by [[Ghazan]] in 1296<ref name=\":1\" />)\n## Aq Timur\n# Karai (died in infancy)\n# Changtimur (died in infancy)\n# Tashtimur (died in infancy)\n# Ashightimur (died in infancy)\n# akash m (died in infancy)\n== References ==\n<references />\n[[Category:1284 deaths]]\n[[Category:Ilkhanate]]\n[[Category:Mongol Empire people]]\n", "text_old": "{{copy edit|date=April 2020}}\n\n{{Infobox royalty|name=Qonqurtai|spouse-type=|regent=|queen=|religion=|mother=Ajuja|father=[[Hulagu Khan]]|house-type=Dynasty|house=[[Borjigin]]|issue=|death_place=[[Karabakh]], [[Ilkhanate]]|image=|death_date=18 January 1284|birth_place=[[Mongolia]]|birth_date=|successor=|predecessor=|reign=1277 - 1282 <br> 12 July 1282 - 18 January 1284|succession=Viceroy of [[Anatolia]]|caption=|reg-type=}}'''Qonqurtai''' ({{Lang-fa|\u0642\u0648\u0646\u0642\u0648\u0631\u062a\u0627\u0649}}) was a Mongal prince and viceroy of [[Anatolia]] for the [[Ilkhanate]] [[khanate]].\n\n== Life ==\nQonqurtai was born to [[Hulagu Khan]] and Ajuja Aguchi, his [[Khitan people|Khitan]] concubine wife. Qonqurtai was Hulagu's ninth son and was the senior commander during the reign of his brother [[Abaqa Khan|Abaqa]]. He was twice appointed as viceroy of Anatolia, firstly during the reign of Abaqa and then under [[Tekuder]]. His winter quarters were in [[:tr: Kazova|Kazova]] plains near [[Tokat]], while his viceroyalty itself has centered around [[Kayseri]].\n\n== Rule in Anatolia ==\nHe was appointed as commander of Ilkhanid army in Anatolia with [[Shams al-Din Juvayni]] as his vizier after the [[Battle of Elbistan]] in 1277 to support the [[Sultanate of Rum]] against revolting Turcomans.<ref>{{Cite book|last=Lane, George, 1952-|first=|url=https://www.worldcat.org/oclc/890796255|title=Early Mongol rule in thirteenth-century Iran : a Persian renaissance|publisher=|year=|isbn=978-1-134-43103-8|location=London|pages=201|oclc=890796255}}</ref>He pursed [[Jimri]], a claimant to Seljuk throne and attacked his patrons - the [[Karamanids]]. As a consequence, [[Mehmet I of Karaman]] was captured and executed together with his sons Mahmud and Karaman in October 1277.<ref>{{Cite book|last=|first=|url=https://www.worldcat.org/oclc/219570995|title=The Cambridge history of Turkey|publisher=|others=Fleet, Kate., Faroqhi, Suraiya, 1941-, Kasaba, Re\u015fat, 1954-|year=|isbn=978-0-521-62093-2|location=New York|pages=70|oclc=219570995}}</ref> He further authorised [[S\u00e2hib Ata]] to act on his behalf. He aided [[Kaykhusraw III]]'s efforts to subdue Karamanids and [[Eshrefids]] in 1282. However, he had to cease his activities upon hearing death of Abaqa.\n\nUpon the death of [[Abaqa Khan|Abaqa]], he supported [[Tekuder]]'s succession in [[Maragheh|Maragha]], who in return gave him the hand of Toqiyatai Khatun, a [[Keraites|Keraite]] concubine of Hulagu and niece of [[Doquz Khatun|Dokuz Khatun]] on 12 July 1282. He was also re-appointed as viceroy of Anatolia the same day.<ref>{{Cite book|last=Nicola|first=Bruno De|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=MjZYDwAAQBAJ|title=Women in Mongol Iran: The Khatuns, 1206-1335|date=2017-03-08|publisher=Edinburgh University Press|isbn=978-1-4744-1549-1|language=en}}</ref>However, later in Tekuder's reign, he shifted his alliance to [[Arghun]], which made the former suspicious. Qonqurtai was summoned to Karabakh, accused of conspiracy and was arrested by Teg\u00fcder's son-in-law, Alinaq - the viceroy of [[Georgia (country)|Georgia]] on 17 January 1284 and was executed next day by breaking his neck.<ref>{{Cite book|last=Nicola|first=Bruno De|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=RgpRDAAAQBAJ|title=The Mongols' Middle East: Continuity and Transformation in Ilkhanid Iran|last2=Melville|first2=Charles|date=2016-06-09|publisher=BRILL|year=|isbn=978-90-04-31472-6|location=|pages=113|language=en}}</ref> Later Arghun had put Tekuder on trial for Qonqurtai's death, who suffered the same penalty as him.\n\n== Personality ==\nHe was described as a wise ruler in ''[[Zafarnamah (Mustawfi)|Zafarnamah]]'' by [[Hamdallah Mustawfi|Hamdullah Mustawfi]]<ref name=\":0\">L. J. Ward, \u201cThe \u1e92afar-n\u0101mah of \u1e24amd All\u0101h Mustaufi and the Il-Kh\u0101n dynasty of Iran,\u201d Ph.D. diss, p.204, University of Manchester, 1983.</ref>, while [[Al-Mansur Qalawun|Qalawun]] considered him as a dishonorable and cruel man.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Allouche|first=Adel|date=1990|title=Teg\u00fcder's Ultimatum to Qalawun|url=https://www.cambridge.org/core/product/identifier/S0020743800034358/type/journal_article|journal=International Journal of Middle East Studies|language=en|volume=22|issue=4|pages=437\u2013446|doi=10.1017/S0020743800034358|issn=0020-7438|via=}}</ref>\n\n== Family ==\nHe was married to Toqiyatai Khatun (d. 1292), a [[Keraites|Keraite]] concubine of Hulagu and niece of [[Doquz Khatun|Dokuz Khatun]] on 12 July 1282, and only two of his children reached adulthood.<ref name=\":0\" />:\n\n# Esen Timur Kharbanda (executed by [[Ghazan]] in 1296<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|url=https://deepblue.lib.umich.edu/handle/2027.42/133445|title=Mediating Sacred Kingship: Conversion and Sovereignty in Mongol Iran|website=deepblue.lib.umich.edu|access-date=2020-04-06}}</ref>)\n## Pulad\n# Ildar (executed by [[Ghazan]] in 1296<ref name=\":1\" />)\n## Aq Timur\n# Karai (died in infancy)\n# Changtimur (died in infancy)\n# Tashtimur (died in infancy)\n# Ashightimur (died in infancy)\n# akash m (died in infancy)\n== References ==\n<references />\n[[Category:1284 deaths]]\n[[Category:Ilkhanate]]\n[[Category:Mongol Empire people]]\n", "name_user": "Ssawp", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eLife", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Qonqurtai"}
{"title_page": "Olivia Physical", "text_new": "{{Infobox album\n| name       = Olivia Physical\n| type       = video\n| artist     = [[Olivia Newton-John]]\n| cover      = OliviaPhysical.jpg\n| border     = yes\n| alt        =\n| released   = February 8, 1982\n| recorded   = 1978\u20131982\n| venue      =\n| studio     =\n| genre      = [[Music video]]\n| length     = 54 minutes\n| label      = [[Universal Pictures Home Entertainment|MCA Home Video]]\n| director   = [[Brian Grant (director)|Brian Grant]]\n| producer   = [[Olivia Newton-John]], Scott Millaney, [[John Farrar]]\n| prev_title =\n| prev_year  =\n| next_title = [[Olivia in Concert]]\n| next_year  = 1983\n}}\n\n'''''Olivia Physical''''' is a 1982 video collection featuring the singer [[Olivia Newton-John]] and various of her songs, most from the album ''[[Physical (album)|Physical]]''. A somewhat expanded version of the video was aired as an [[American Broadcasting Company|ABC]] prime-time [[television special]], ''Let's Get Physical'',<ref>{{cite web|last=Arrington |first=Carl |url=http://www.people.com/people/archive/article/0,,20081457,00.html |title=Olivia Gets Physical - Personal Success, Matt Lattanzi, Olivia Newton-John : People.com |publisher=People.com |date= |accessdate=2008-11-27}}</ref> which was in the top 10 of the [[Nielsen ratings]]. In 1983 the video received a [[Grammy Award]] as [[Grammy Award for Video of the Year|Video of the Year]].<ref>[https://www.grammy.com/grammys/awards/25th-annual-grammy-awards 25th Annual Grammy Awards (1982)]</ref><ref>Dennis McDougal, ''The Last Mogul: Lew Wasserman, MCA, and the Hidden History of Hollywood'' (New York: Da Capo, 2001), [https://books.google.com/books?id=6XCIqw48uSwC&pg=PA407&dq=%22Olivia+Physical%22 p. 407].</ref>\n\n==Track listing==\n{{Track listing\n| extra_column    = Director(s)\n\n| title1          = [[Landslide (Olivia Newton-John song)|Landslide]]\n| extra1          = [[Brian Grant (director)|Brian Grant]]\n| length1         = 4:27\n\n| title2          = [[Magic (Olivia Newton-John song)|Magic]]\n| note2           = from the motion picture ''[[Xanadu (film)|Xanadu]]''\n| extra2          = Grant\n| length2         = 4:31\n\n| title3          = [[Physical (Olivia Newton-John song)|Physical]]\n| extra3          = Grant\n| length3         = 3:44\n\n| title4          = [[Physical (album)|Carried Away]]\n| extra4          = Grant\n| length4         = 3:43\n\n| title5          = [[A Little More Love (Olivia Newton-John song)|A Little More Love]]\n| note5           = from the album ''[[Totally Hot]]''\n| extra5          = Grant\n| length5         = 3:27\n\n| title6          = [[Physical (album)|Recovery]]\n| extra6          = Grant\n| length6         = 4:18\n\n| title7          = [[Physical (album)|The Promise (The Dolphin Song)]]\n| extra7          = Grant\n| length7         = 4:33\n\n| title8          = [[Physical (album)|Love Make Me Strong]]\n| extra8          = Grant\n| length8         = 3:10\n\n| title9          = [[Physical (album)|Stranger's Touch]]\n| extra9          = Grant\n| length9         = 3:49\n\n| title10         = [[Make a Move on Me]]\n| extra10         = Grant\n| length10        = 3:17\n\n| title11         = [[Physical (album)|Falling]]\n| extra11         = Grant\n| length11        = 3:45\n\n| title12         = [[Physical (album)|Silvery Rain]]\n| extra12         = Grant\n| length12        = 3:39\n\n| title13         = [[Hopelessly Devoted to You]]\n| note13           = from the motion picture ''[[Grease (film)|Grease]]''\n| extra13         = Grant\n| length13        = 3:05\n\n| title14         = Credits\n| length14        = 0:51\n}}\n\n;Note\n* The television version has little differences from the home video version. The television version features video interludes starring Olivia, introducing some music videos. The home video version doesn't, but it features the music videos for \"Love Make Me Strong\" and \"Falling\", which weren't part of the television version.<ref name=\"oophysical\">{{cite web|url=http://www.onlyolivia.com/visual/tv/80/81/81physical/index.html|title=Only Olivia \u2014 ''Olivia Physical''|publisher=Onlyolivia.com|accessdate=19 February 2015}}</ref>\n\n==Legacy==\nNewton-John was one of the first artists to invest in music videos. The 1978 album ''Totally Hot'' was her first one to features videos accompanying all the singles from the album, but they were very simple, being primarily composed of Newton-John singing in the studio. The music videos of the songs of ''Physical'' are more complex, and were one of the firsts to present a plot line, and not just a video of the artist performing the song. According to ''Olivia Physical'' video album director, Brian Grant, Newton-John record company and management were reluctant about the project at the first moment: \"I suppose there was a little nervousness at first. But, [Olivia] got us out here because she liked what we had done [...]\".<ref name=\"bbbrian\">{{cite journal|last=Darling|first=Cary|date=1981-08-29|title=Grant of U.K. Tackling Newton-John Video|journal=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]|location=New York|volume=93|issue=34|issn=0006-2510|url={{Google books |plainurl=yes |id=QiQEAAAAMBAJ |page=29 }} |ref=harv}}</ref> Newton-John herself was a supporter of the music video industry, as she commented in a ''Billboard'' article about the ''Olivia Physical'' production:\n\n<blockquote>\n\"I think this is the way albums will go in the future: visuals with the music. I got to be a different personality and play another side of myself.\"<ref name=\"bbnewalbum\">{{cite journal|last=Harrison|first=Ed|date=1981-10-10|title=Newton-John Maturity Evident On New Album|journal=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]|location=New York|volume=93|issue=40|issn=0006-2510 |url={{Google books |plainurl=yes |id=niQEAAAAMBAJ |page=37 }} |ref=harv}}</ref>\n</blockquote>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Olivia Newton-John}}\n\n[[Category:Olivia Newton-John video albums]]\n[[Category:Music video compilation albums]]\n[[Category:1982 video albums]]\n[[Category:1982 compilation albums]]\n[[Category:Grammy Award for Video of the Year]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox album\n| name       = Olivia Physical\n| type       = video\n| artist     = [[Olivia Newton-John]]\n| cover      = OliviaPhysical.jpg\n| border     = yes\n| alt        =\n| released   = February 8, 1982\n| recorded   = 1978\u20131982\n| venue      =\n| studio     =\n| genre      = [[Music video]]\n| length     = 54 minutes\n| label      = [[Universal Pictures Home Entertainment|MCA Home Video]]\n| director   = [[Brian Grant (director)|Brian Grant]]\n| producer   = [[Olivia Newton-John]], Scott Millaney, [[John Farrar]]\n| prev_title =\n| prev_year  =\n| next_title = [[Olivia in Concert]]\n| next_year  = 1983\n}}\n\n'''''Olivia Physical''''' is a 1982 video collection featuring the singer [[Olivia Newton-John]] and various of her songs, most from the album ''[[Physical (album)|Physical]]''. A somewhat expanded version of the video was aired as an [[American Broadcasting Company|ABC]] prime-time [[television special]], ''Let's Get Physical'',<ref>{{cite web|last=Arrington |first=Carl |url=http://www.people.com/people/archive/article/0,,20081457,00.html |title=Olivia Gets Physical - Personal Success, Matt Lattanzi, Olivia Newton-John : People.com |publisher=People.com |date= |accessdate=2008-11-27}}</ref> which was in the top 10 of the [[Nielsen ratings]]. In 1983 the video received a [[Grammy Award]] as [[Grammy Award for Video of the Year|Video of the Year]].<ref>[https://www.grammy.com/grammys/awards/25th-annual-grammy-awards 25th Annual Grammy Awards (1982)]</ref><ref>Dennis McDougal, ''The Last Mogul: Lew Wasserman, MCA, and the Hidden History of Hollywood'' (New York: Da Capo, 2001), [https://books.google.com/books?id=6XCIqw48uSwC&pg=PA407&dq=%22Olivia+Physical%22 p. 407].</ref>\n\n==Track listing==\n{{Track listing\n| extra_column    = Director(s)\n\n| title1          = [[Landslide (Olivia Newton-John song)|Landslide]]\n| extra1          = [[Brian Grant (director)|Brian Grant]]\n| length1         = 4:27\n\n| title2          = [[Magic (Olivia Newton-John song)|Magic]]\n| note2           = from the motion picture ''[[Xanadu (film)|Xanadu]]''\n| extra2          = Grant\n| length2         = 4:31\n\n| title3          = [[Physical (Olivia Newton-John song)|Physical]]\n| extra3          = Grant\n| length3         = 3:44\n\n| title4          = [[Physical (album)|Carried Away]]\n| extra4          = Grant\n| length4         = 3:43\n\n| title5          = [[A Little More Love (Olivia Newton-John song)|A Little More Love]]\n| note5           = from the album ''[[Totally Hot]]''\n| extra5          = Grant\n| length5         = 3:27\n\n| title6          = [[Physical (album)|Recovery]]\n| extra6          = Grant\n| length6         = 4:18\n\n| title7          = [[Physical (album)|The Promise (The Dolphin Song)]]\n| extra7          = Grant\n| length7         = 4:33\n\n| title8          = [[Physical (album)|Love Make Me Strong]]\n| extra8          = Grant\n| length8         = 3:10\n\n| title9          = [[Physical (album)|Stranger's Touch]]\n| extra9          = Grant\n| length9         = 3:49\n\n| title10         = [[Make a Move on Me]]\n| extra10         = Grant\n| length10        = 3:17\n\n| title11         = [[Physical (album)|Falling]]\n| extra11         = Grant\n| length11        = 3:45\n\n| title12         = [[Physical (album)|Silvery Rain]]\n| extra12         = Grant\n| length12        = 3:39\n\n| title13         = [[Hopelessly Devoted to You]]\n| note13           = from the motion picture ''[[Grease (film)|Grease]]''\n| extra13         = Grant\n| length13        = 3:05\n\n| title14         = Credits\n| length14        = 0:51\n}}\n\n;Note\n* The television version has little differences from the home video version. The television version features video interludes starring Olivia, introducing some music videos. The home video version doesn't, but it features the music videos for \"Love Make Me Strong\" and \"Falling\", which weren't part of the television version.<ref name=\"oophysical\">{{cite web|url=http://www.onlyolivia.com/visual/tv/80/81/81physical/index.html|title=Only Olivia \u2014 ''Olivia Physical''|publisher=Onlyolivia.com|accessdate=19 February 2015}}</ref>\n\n==Legacy==\nNewton-John was one of the first artists to invest in music videos. The 1978 album ''Totally Hot'' was her first one to features videos accompanying all the singles from the album, but they were very simple, being primarily composed of Newton-John singing in the studio. The music videos of the songs of ''Physical'' are more complex, and were one of the firsts to present a plot line, and not just a video of the artist performing the song. According to ''Olivia Physical'' video album director, Brian Grant, Newton-John record company and management were reluctant about the project at the first moment: \"I suppose there was a little nervousness at first. But, [Olivia] got us out here because she liked what we had done [...]\".<ref name=\"bbbrian\">{{cite journal|last=Darling|first=Cary|date=1981-08-29|title=Grant of U.K. Tackling Newton-John Video|journal=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]|location=New York|volume=93|issue=34|issn=0006-2510|url={{Google books |plainurl=yes |id=QiQEAAAAMBAJ |page=29 }} |ref=harv}}</ref> Newton-John herself was a supporter of the music video industry, as she commented in a ''Billboard'' article about the ''Olivia Physical'' production:\n\n<blockquote>\n\"I think this is the way albums will go in the future: visuals with the music. I got to be a different personality and play an other side of myself.\"<ref name=\"bbnewalbum\">{{cite journal|last=Harrison|first=Ed|date=1981-10-10|title=Newton-John Maturity Evident On New Album|journal=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]|location=New York|volume=93|issue=40|issn=0006-2510 |url={{Google books |plainurl=yes |id=niQEAAAAMBAJ |page=37 }} |ref=harv}}</ref>\n</blockquote>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Olivia Newton-John}}\n\n[[Category:Olivia Newton-John video albums]]\n[[Category:Music video compilation albums]]\n[[Category:1982 video albums]]\n[[Category:1982 compilation albums]]\n[[Category:Grammy Award for Video of the Year]]\n", "name_user": "WereSpielChequers", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eLegacy:Typo fixing, replaced: an other  \u2192  another", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Olivia_Physical"}
{"title_page": "Osborne Dam", "text_new": "{{Infobox dam\n|name                 =Osborne Dam\n|image                =Osborne spillway.jpg \n|image_caption        =Osborne Spillway\n|name_official        =Osborne Dam\n|dam_crosses          =[[Odzi River]]\n|res_name             =\n|location             =[[Mutare]]\n|dam_length           =1007 metres\n|dam_height           = 66 metres\n|construction_began   =1991\n|res_capacity_total   =400 million cubic metres\n|res_catchment        =1392 km\u00b2\n|res_surface          =2600 ha\n| coordinates          = {{coord|18|45|59|S|32|29|08|E|type:landmark_region:ZW|display=inline,title}}\n| extra                =\n}}\nThe '''Osborne Dam''' site on the [[Odzi River]], [[Zimbabwe]], was identified in the 1950s by the planning engineers of the Ministry of Water.  Cored drilling investigations on the two possible alignments were completed in the 1960s.  After the completion of Mazvikadei dam [1985\u2013'88] under Italian aid finance, further funding became available for the project and when the 10 000 hectares of potential irrigable land was identified downstream the project was approved in 1989 by the multi-ministry irrigation committee of the Zimbabwe Government.\n\n==Technical details==\nOsborne Dam is an earth embankment dam, creating a reservoir with a surface area of 2600 hectares, storing 400,000 megalitres on the [[Odzi River]], a tributary of the [[Save River (Africa)|Save River]], in [[Zimbabwe]]  The catchment area is 1392&nbsp;km\u00b2 the embankment is 66 metres high, crest length 1007 metres and the volume of earth in the embankment is 5.1 Million cubic metres.  The spillway is the \"drop inlet\" type with a crest radius of 15.7 metres, a 6-metre diameter shaft and conduit conveys the overflow to the flip bucket.  The catchment area of 2 400 square kilometres stretches up to the source of the Odzi river in the high rainfall area just south of Juliasdale.  The construction was financed with aid supplied by the Italian Government, the main contractor was Salini Costuttori SpA, with local subcontractors K.W.Blasting doing tunneling and hard excavation.<ref>{{cite journal|author=Symphorian, G.R., Madamombe, E., van der Zaag, P.|title=Dam operation for environmental water releases; the case of Osborne dam, Save catchment, Zimbabwe|journal=Physics and Chemistry of the Earth|volume=28|issue=20\u201327|pages=985\u2013993|date=2003|doi=10.1016/j.pce.2003.08.012}}</ref> It is operated to supply water to irrigation schemes in [[Chimanimani District|Chimanimani]] and [[Chipinge District|Chipinge]] districts.<ref>{{cite journal|author=Love, F., Madamombe, E., Marshall, B., Kaseke, E.|title=Preliminary estimate of environmental flow requirements of the Rusape River, Zimbabwe |journal=Physics and Chemistry of the Earth|volume=31|issue=15\u201316 |pages=864\u2013869|date=2006|doi=10.1016/j.pce.2006.08.005}}</ref>\n\n==Recreational park==\nThe lake stretches for 16 kilometres up to the Odzi River and 15 kilometres along its Nyatande tributary. The lake is over 6 kilometres wide and 66 metres deep. The area has a moderate climate with an average temperature of 24 degrees Celsius.\n\nFacilities available at Osborne Dam include a rest camp and a camping site.\nA rest camp with self-catering lodges is located at a vantage point overlooking the lake.\nThe large camping site can accommodate 300 campers has braai facilities and electric points distributed at every other site and is an ideal location for fishing and boating tournaments.\n\nActivities\n*Fishing \u2013 one of the most popular activities. Bass Masters Societies view this dam as potential record catch territory. Anglers will most certainly enjoy this experience in the generally cool environs.\n*Boating \u2013 the vast water body gives boating enthusiasts an expansive area to race or just cruise around.\n*Birding \u2013 this an increasingly popular activity as the park has become home to a wide range of aquatic and terrestrial birds.\n*Walking safaris \u2013 walking paths along the dam wall and around the shores, down the Odzi River and in the nearby hills (Mt Jenya) provide a wide range of scenery for trail enthusiasts.\n*Game drive \u2013 there is a 102 kilometre drive around the lake which includes access to several of the nearby rural areas.\n*Pony rides \u2013 pony rides around the lake shore can be arranged with the tourist office\n*Windsurfing \u2013 Ideal conditions with a steady western breeze\n*Canoeing \u2013 Beautiful inlets and waterways for the canoe enthusiast.\n\n==Image gallery==\n\n<gallery>\nFile:Osborne20.jpg|Downstream face\nFile:Osborne 017.jpg|Before first filling\nFile:Osbo Aug 2010 5.jpg|Spillway and outlet bridge 2010\nFile:Osborne7.jpg|Spillway discharging\nFile:Osborne1 93.jpg|Final stages of construction\nFile:Osborne7 92.jpg|After first year of construction\nFile:Osborne aerial.jpg|Aerial view after construction. 35% full\n</gallery>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n[[Category:Dams in Zimbabwe]]\n[[Category:Tourist attractions in Manicaland Province]]\n[[Category:Buildings and structures in Manicaland Province]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox dam\n|name                 =Osborne Dam\n|image                =Osborne spillway.jpg \n|image_caption        =Osborne Spillway\n|name_official        =Osborne Dam\n|dam_crosses          =[[Odzi River]]\n|res_name             =\n|location             =[[Mutare]]\n|dam_length           =1007 metres\n|dam_height           = 66 metres\n|construction_began   =1991\n|res_capacity_total   =400 million cubic metres\n|res_catchment        =1392 km\u00b2\n|res_surface          =2600 ha\n| coordinates          = {{coord|18|45|59|S|32|29|08|E|type:landmark_region:ZW|display=inline,title}}\n| extra                =\n}}\nThe '''Osborne Dam''' site on the [[Odzi River]], [[Zimbabwe]], was identified in the 1950s by the planning engineers of the Ministry of Water.  Cored drilling investigations on the two possible alignments were completed in the 1960s.  After the completion of Mazvikadei dam [1985\u2013'88] under Italian aid finance, further funding became available for the project and when the 10 000 hectares of potential irrigable land was identified downstream the project was approved in 1989 by the multi-ministry irrigation committee of the Zimbabwe Government.\n\n==Technical details==\nOsborne Dam is an earth embankment dam, creating a reservoir with a surface area of 2600 hectares, storing 400,000 megalitres on the [[Odzi River]], a tributary of the [[Save River (Africa)|Save River]], in [[Zimbabwe]]  The catchment area is 1392&nbsp;km\u00b2 the embankment is 66 metres high, crest length 1007 metres and the volume of earth in the embankment is 5.1 Million cubic metres.  The spillway is the \"drop inlet\" type with a crest radius of 15.7 metres, a 6-metre diameter shaft and conduit conveys the overflow to the flip bucket.  The catchment area of 2 400 square kilometres stretches up to the source of the Odzi river in the high rainfall area just south of Juliasdale.  The construction was financed with aid supplied by the Italian Government, the main contractor was Salini Costuttori SpA, with local subcontractors K.W.Blasting doing tunneling and hard excavation.<ref>{{cite journal|author=Symphorian, G.R., Madamombe, E., van der Zaag, P.|title=Dam operation for environmental water releases; the case of Osborne dam, Save catchment, Zimbabwe|journal=Physics and Chemistry of the Earth|volume=28|issue=20\u201327|pages=985\u2013993|date=2003|doi=10.1016/j.pce.2003.08.012}}</ref> It is operated to supply water to irrigation schemes in [[Chimanimani]] and [[Chipinge]] Districts.<ref>{{cite journal|author=Love, F., Madamombe, E., Marshall, B., Kaseke, E.|title=Preliminary estimate of environmental flow requirements of the Rusape River, Zimbabwe |journal=Physics and Chemistry of the Earth|volume=31|issue=15\u201316 |pages=864\u2013869|date=2006|doi=10.1016/j.pce.2006.08.005}}</ref>\n\n==Recreational park==\nThe lake stretches for 16 kilometres up to the Odzi River and 15 kilometres along its Nyatande tributary. The lake is over 6 kilometres wide and 66 metres deep. The area has a moderate climate with an average temperature of 24 degrees Celsius.\n\nFacilities available at Osborne Dam include a rest camp and a camping site.\nA rest camp with self-catering lodges is located at a vantage point overlooking the lake.\nThe large camping site can accommodate 300 campers has braai facilities and electric points distributed at every other site and is an ideal location for fishing and boating tournaments.\n\nActivities\n*Fishing \u2013 one of the most popular activities. Bass Masters Societies view this dam as potential record catch territory. Anglers will most certainly enjoy this experience in the generally cool environs.\n*Boating \u2013 the vast water body gives boating enthusiasts an expansive area to race or just cruise around.\n*Birding \u2013 this an increasingly popular activity as the park has become home to a wide range of aquatic and terrestrial birds.\n*Walking safaris \u2013 walking paths along the dam wall and around the shores, down the Odzi River and in the nearby hills (Mt Jenya) provide a wide range of scenery for trail enthusiasts.\n*Game drive \u2013 there is a 102 kilometre drive around the lake which includes access to several of the nearby rural areas.\n*Pony rides \u2013 pony rides around the lake shore can be arranged with the tourist office\n*Windsurfing \u2013 Ideal conditions with a steady western breeze\n*Canoeing \u2013 Beautiful inlets and waterways for the canoe enthusiast.\n\n==Image gallery==\n\n<gallery>\nFile:Osborne20.jpg|Downstream face\nFile:Osborne 017.jpg|Before first filling\nFile:Osbo Aug 2010 5.jpg|Spillway and outlet bridge 2010\nFile:Osborne7.jpg|Spillway discharging\nFile:Osborne1 93.jpg|Final stages of construction\nFile:Osborne7 92.jpg|After first year of construction\nFile:Osborne aerial.jpg|Aerial view after construction. 35% full\n</gal